SIMPLE: tug
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tug
<hw>Tug</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Tugged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tugging</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>toggen</ets>; akin to
OD. <ets>tocken</ets> to entice, G. <ets>zucken</ets> to jerk, draw,
Icel. <ets>toga</ets> to draw, AS. <ets>t⟦eacute⟧on</ets>, p. p.
<ets>togen</ets>, to draw, G. <ets>ziehen</ets>, OHG. <ets>ziohan</ets>,
Goth. <ets>tiuhan</ets>, L. <ets>ducere</ets> to lead, draw. Cf.
<er>Duke</er>, <er>Team</er>, <er>Tie</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>,
<er>Touch</er>, <er>Tow</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, <er>Tuck</er> to press
in, <er>Toy</er> a plaything.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To pull or draw
with great effort; to draw along with continued exertion; to haul along;
to tow; <as>as, to <ex>tug</ex> a loaded cart; to <ex>tug</ex> a ship
into port.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There sweat, there strain, <qex>tug</qex> the laborious oar.</q>
<rj><qau>Roscommon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To pull; to pluck.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To ease the pain,⟦br⟧
His <qex>tugged</qex> cars suffered with a strain.</q>
<rj><qau>Hudibras.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tug</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tug
<hw>Tug</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To pull with great
effort; to strain in labor; <as>as, to <ex>tug</ex> at the oar; to
<ex>tug</ex> against the stream</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>tugged</qex>, he shook, till down they came.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To labor; to strive; to struggle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>England now is left⟦br⟧
To <qex>tug</qex> and scamble and to part by the teeth⟦br⟧
The unowed interest of proud-swelling state.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tug</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tug
<hw>Tug</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A pull with the utmost
effort, as in the athletic contest called <xex>tug of war</xex>; a
supreme effort.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At the <qex>tug</qex> he falls,⟦br⟧
Vast ruins come along, rent from the smoking walls.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A sort of vehicle, used for conveying timber and
heavy articles.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A small, powerful steamboat used
to tow vessels; -- called also <altname>steam tug</altname>,
<altname>tugboat</altname>, and <altname>towboat</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A trace, or drawing strap, of a harness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mining.)</fld> <def>An iron hook of a hoisting tub,
to which a tackle is affixed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Tug iron</b></col>, <cd>an iron hook or button to which a
tug or trace may be attached, as on the shaft of a wagon.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tugan</ent>⟦br⟧
